14 CAPACITY TO PROCEED PROCESS
15 SECTION 6.(a) G.S. 7B-2401.2 reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 7B-2401.2. Procedures to determine capacity; hearing procedures; evidence.
17 …
18 (e) Any report made to the court pursuant to this section shall be forwarded to the clerk
19 of superior court in a sealed envelope addressed to the attention of a presiding judge, with a
20 covering statement to the clerk of the fact of the examination of the juvenile and any conclusion
21 as to whether the juvenile has or lacks capacity to proceed. If the juvenile is being held in the
22 custody of the Division, the The clerk shall send a copy of the covering statement to the Division.
23 The Division and any persons employed by the Division shall maintain the copy of the covering
24 statement as a confidential record. A copy of the full report shall be forwarded to the juvenile's
25 counsel. If the question of the juvenile's capacity to proceed is raised at any time, a copy of the
26 full report must be forwarded to the prosecutor. Until the question of the juvenile's capacity is
27 raised, the full report to the court shall be kept under such conditions as are directed by the court,
28 and its contents shall not be revealed except the report and the relevant confidential information
29 previously ordered released under G.S. 7B-2401.3(c) shall be released to the program where the
30 juvenile is receiving remediation services and as directed by the court. revealed. Any report made
31 to the court pursuant to this section shall be maintained as a confidential record.
32 …
33 (h) When the capacity of the juvenile to proceed is questioned, the court shall hold a
34 hearing to determine the juvenile's capacity to proceed. If an evaluation is ordered pursuant to
35 subsection (b) of this section, the hearing shall be held upon receipt of the forensic evaluation
36 report. The clerk shall provide notice to the juvenile and juvenile, the prosecutor prosecutor, and
37 the chief court counselor in accordance with G.S. 7B-1807. The order of the court shall contain
38 findings of fact to support its determination of the juvenile's capacity to proceed. The parties may
39 stipulate that the juvenile is capable to proceed but shall not be allowed to stipulate that the
40 juvenile lacks capacity to proceed. If the court finds the juvenile is capable to proceed, the
41 juvenile proceedings shall no longer be stayed, and the court shall set a date for such further
42 proceedings. If the juvenile's capacity to proceed is contested, the juvenile bears the burden of
43 proving the juvenile is incapable to proceed by a preponderance of the evidence. At a contested
44 hearing, the State and the juvenile may call witnesses and present evidence. Nothing in this
45 subsection may be construed to prohibit the State or the juvenile from calling other expert
46 witnesses to testify at a capacity hearing. If appropriate, the If the court finds that the juvenile is
47 not capable to proceed, the court must determine if the juvenile is substantially likely to attain
48 capacity in the foreseeable future. If the court finds that the juvenile is substantially likely to
49 attain capacity in the foreseeable future, the court may order remediation services in accordance
50 with G.S. 7B-2401.4.
51 …."
