1 SECTION 6.(b) G.S. 7B-2401.4 reads as rewritten:
2 "§ 7B-2401.4. Remediation.
3 …
4 (b) When the court finds the juvenile incapable to proceed, and substantially likely to
5 attain capacity in the foreseeable future, the court may order remediation services. The
6 remediation services shall be based on the recommendations from the forensic evaluation. All
7 forensic evaluations for the juvenile and the relevant confidential information previously ordered
8 released under G.S. 7B-2401.3(c) shall be released to the program or programs where the juvenile
9 is receiving remediation services as directed by the court.
10 …
11 (e) An order for remediation services shall contain all of the following:
12 (1) Written findings of fact regarding the least restrictive environment for the
13 remediation services.
14 (2) If the court order allows for secure confinement pursuant to subsection (d) of
15 this section, the maximum time for placement in a secure facility shall be
16 pursuant to subsection (f) of this section.
17 (3) Whether remediation services shall include mental health treatment to reduce
18 interfering symptoms, specialized psychoeducational programming, or a
19 combination of these interventions. If both mental health services and
20 psychoeducational programming are ordered, the court shall identify a
21 provider for each service.
22 …
23 (g) The Division shall be responsible for the provision of psychoeducation remediation
24 programming and working with community partners to secure any additional services
25 recommended in the forensic evaluation report. The Division is authorized to contract with the
26 University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill or any other qualified educational organization to
27 develop and conduct related trainings and curriculum.
28 The remediation service provider or providers shall provide reports to the court at least every
29 90 days. Any report made to the court pursuant to this subsection shall be forwarded to the clerk
30 of superior court addressed to the attention of the presiding judge. judge and to the juvenile's
31 attorney. A report provided under this subsection shall include all of the following:
32 (1) The dates of any services provided to the juvenile.
33 (2) A summary of the juvenile's attendance and participation.
34 (3) Information about the juvenile's progress in the areas that were found to be
35 relevant to the juvenile's incapacity, incapacity and that are the focus of the
36 provider's services, including education regarding court procedures and
37 stabilization or improvement of symptoms leading to functional impairments.
38 No statement or disclosure made by the juvenile during the remediation services regarding
39 the juvenile's responsibility for a criminal act that can result either in an adjudication of
40 delinquency or transfer of a matter to superior court for trial as an adult is admissible in any
41 juvenile or criminal proceeding against the juvenile or defendant. All remediation progress
42 reports, summaries, and notes shall not include any such statement.
43 The court shall hold a hearing within 30 days of receipt of the remediation progress report to
44 review the remediation services. The remediation review hearing may be informal, and the court
45 may consider all remediation progress reports. The court may consider any evidence, including
46 hearsay evidence as defined in G.S. 8C-1, Rule 801, that the court finds to be relevant, reliable,
47 and necessary to determine if remediation services should continue or reassessment of capacity
48 is warranted. The juvenile and the juvenile's parent, guardian, or custodian shall have an
49 opportunity to present evidence, and they may advise the court concerning the remediation
50 services. The order of the court may be amended or supplemented only as provided in this
51 Subchapter and only after notice and a hearing.
